# RDF 3.0.5 Release Notes

## Context Audit Command

Adds `/r-context-audit` as the command driver for the existing `state/context-audit.sh`
measurement script. Produces a scored health report (0-100, CLEAN/NEEDS_WORK/BLOATED/
CRITICAL) covering always-loaded boot cost, rdf-state.sh field waste detection,
work-output accumulation across projects, and session history totals. Findings
are sorted by impact with one-line fix suggestions. Supports `--save-baseline` for
drift tracking (`~/.rdf/context-audit-baseline.json`) and `--fix` to auto-apply
Tier 1 quick wins. Designed for weekly health checks, post-refresh verification,
and quarterly baseline comparisons.

## Slop Audit Command Promotion

Promotes `/r-util-slop-scan` to `/r-audit-slop` with two additional verification
passes over HIGH findings: an independent sentinel peer-review pass
(`rdf-reviewer`) and an engineer FP-validation pass (`rdf-engineer`, read-only).
Only findings that survive both passes appear in the final report, substantially
reducing false positives. The `--quick` flag restores single-agent behavior
equivalent to the former command. Discovery-first protocol and density safeguards
are unchanged.

## BATS Adapter Test Suite

Adds a hermetic BATS test suite (`tests/adapter.bats`) with 7 tests covering
the full `rdf generate claude-code` round-trip: file tree generation, canonical
body preservation, `.rdf-hash` sidecar emission (Phase 7 regression), idempotency
on second run, and drift detection (corrupted deployed file cited in
`rdf doctor --scope content-drift` output). Tests use `mktemp -d` for isolation
and do not pollute `/root/.claude/` or `~/.rdf/`. Includes `tests/Makefile` with
`make test` target using system bats (no batsman submodule — rationale documented
in `tests/README.md`). Phase 9's CI `tests` job activates automatically now that
`tests/Makefile` exists.

## GitHub Actions CI Workflow

Adds `.github/workflows/ci.yml` with three parallel jobs: `lint` (bash -n +
shellcheck on all source shell files), `doctor` (generates adapter output then
runs `rdf doctor --scope content-drift` to verify canonical/generated integrity),
and `tests` (BATS suite, conditional on `tests/Makefile` — stub for Phase 10).
Workflow triggers on push to main and pull requests targeting main.

## Progress Tracking Reference

Consolidates the duplicated "Progress Tracking" block from `r-init`, `r-start`,
and `r-save` into a single canonical reference file at
`canonical/reference/progress-tracking.md`. Each command now links to the shared
protocol and retains only its command-specific task names. Eliminates ~53 lines
of duplicated boilerplate across the three command files.

## Doctor Content-Drift Detection

`rdf generate claude-code` now writes a `.rdf-hash` sidecar file next to each
deployed agent and command markdown file. The sidecar contains the SHA-256 hash
of the canonical source body (pre-frontmatter injection). `rdf doctor` gains a
new `content-drift` check that hashes the deployed file body (stripping YAML
frontmatter for agents) and compares it against the sidecar. A mismatch means
the deployed file was modified after the last generate — `rdf doctor` reports
FAIL with the specific file name. A missing sidecar (older deployed trees)
reports WARN and prompts the user to run `rdf generate claude-code`. Run
`rdf doctor --scope content-drift` to check only this category.

## Release Packaging

Adds `.gitattributes` with `export-ignore` rules to prevent dev-only artifacts
from appearing in `git archive` tarballs and GitHub "Download" releases.
Excluded paths: `docs/`, `assets/`, `tests/`, `.github/`, `.rdf/`, `.claude/`,
`.pytest_cache/`, and working files (`CLAUDE.md`, `PLAN.md`, `MEMORY.md`,
`AUDIT.md`). Core consumer-facing content (`canonical/`, `lib/`, `state/`,
`bin/`, `README.md`, `CHANGELOG`) continues to ship.

## Stale Artifact Cleanup

Backlog sweep of stale files identified in the 2026-04-19 framework audit.
Deleted `.pytest_cache/` from the RDF repo (no Python tests). Removed a
521 KB APF branch-diff patch (34 days old) and a 60 KB s3perf misfiled
plan from `.rdf/memory/`. Ran `rotate-work-output.sh` live against four
high-file-count projects: LMD (227 pruned), BFD (175), Sigforge (150),
APF (119). Two conditional targets — `session-safety.md` and
`docs/superpowers/` — were preserved after grep confirmed active
references in `docs/`.

## Work-Output Rotation

Introduces `state/rotate-work-output.sh`, a defensive automation script
that prunes accumulated `.rdf/work-output/` directories across any
RDF-using project.

Age-based pruning deletes `*.md` result files with mtime older than 14 days
(configurable via `--age`). Files whose basename appears in the project's
`PLAN.md` are always preserved regardless of age, protecting in-progress
phase results. If `PLAN.md` is absent, pruning proceeds on age alone.

Size-based truncation keeps `agent-feed.log` bounded: if the file exceeds
100 KB (configurable via `--size-cap`), it is truncated to the last 1000
lines via an atomic `mv` — no data corruption on partial writes.

Flags: `--dry-run` (prints candidates, no modifications), `--age <days>`,
`--size-cap <kb>`. Silently exits 0 when `.rdf/work-output/` does not exist.

`rdf generate claude-code` now deploys `rotate-work-output.sh` to
`~/.rdf/state/` alongside `rdf-state.sh` and `context-audit.sh`.

## Context Audit Timeout Guards

Adds `TIMEOUT_PREFIX` ("timeout 30") to `context-audit.sh` using the same
idiom as `rdf-state.sh`: the git call in the per-repo recency sort and both
`python3` invocations are now guarded. On systems without `timeout`, the
variable is empty and the calls behave as before.

Introduces `_count_md_files()` helper replacing 8 near-duplicate
`find … -name "*.md" … | wc -l` patterns across the skills, agents, memory,
and work-output sections. Also fixes the JSONL byte-accumulation loop: the
previous approach called `stat` once per file; on machines with thousands of
session JSONL files this caused 15+ second stalls. Replaced with
`find -printf '%s\n'` piped to `awk`, reducing Section 8 from ~15s to <0.1s.

## Hang Prevention

Wraps all 14 git invocations in `rdf-state.sh` with a `TIMEOUT_PREFIX`
variable ("timeout 30") to prevent indefinite stalls. Affected scenarios:
`HEAD...@{u}` on an orphaned tracking branch, `.git/index.lock` held by a
crashed process, or a slow/unreachable remote. The `|| echo "<fallback>"`
patterns already silenced error output; they now also catch the non-zero
exit from a fired timeout, so each field degrades gracefully to its
fallback value. On systems without the `timeout` binary (CentOS 6 minimal),
`TIMEOUT_PREFIX` is empty and git calls behave as before.

## Session Startup Fix

Eliminates the `find /` fallback in `/r-start` that caused 120s sandbox
timeouts when invoked from any directory other than the RDF project root.
Root cause: `bash state/rdf-state.sh --full .` used a relative path that
only worked from RDF's own directory, and the documented `{RDF_HOME}`
fallback referenced an undefined variable.

`rdf generate claude-code` now deploys `rdf-state.sh` and
`context-audit.sh` to `~/.rdf/state/` with executable bit, creating the
directory if absent. `/r-start` uses an explicit probe order:
`~/.rdf/state/rdf-state.sh` → `/root/admin/work/proj/rdf/state/rdf-state.sh`
→ inline git fallback. Resolution completes in under 200ms from any project.

## Model Cost Optimization

Adds scope-based model routing to the dispatcher and challenge-mode
Sonnet overrides to command dispatch points. The default session model
shifts from Opus to Sonnet 4.6, with Opus reserved for high-complexity
agent work (engineer multi-file+, sentinel review, planner subagent).

Key changes:
- Dispatcher model routing table: scope:docs and scope:focused downgrade
  engineer to sonnet via Agent model override; multi-file, cross-cutting,
  and sensitive use the engineer's opus default
- Reviewer routing: sentinel dispatches stay opus (agent default);
  challenge dispatches from r-review, r-spec, and r-plan pass
  model: "sonnet" override
- Default session model: settings.json gets "model": "claude-sonnet-4-6"
  — all interactive work, informational commands, and slash commands
  run on Sonnet; agents with explicit model: frontmatter override
  the session default at dispatch time

Design rationale: shell constraint density (Bash 4.1 floor, 8+ distros,
13+ anti-patterns) warrants Opus for implementation and adversarial
review. Mechanical tasks (docs, changelogs, challenge review) run at
full quality on Sonnet. Failure mode of a missing override is Opus on
simple work (waste), never Sonnet on complex work (quality risk).

